phrase: Hi, my name is Susanna Aaron and I am going to do an interview of myself.
My name is Susanna Aaron, A-A-R-O-N.
I was born in Doctors Hospital on January 13, 1960 and my parents brought me home to
their apartment at 269 West 4th Street.
And I have lived in the village pretty much forever since then, you know, with a few departures
to college and so on.
When I was two, when I was – let's see, wait, a little bit about my parents.
My dad came from Brooklyn.
His parents' family – his father had been born in the States, but his father's oldest
brother was born in Russia.
So it was a newly immigrant family, very upwardly mobile.
I think my great uncle, one of them was a lawyer, one of them was a doctor, and my grandfather,
my father's father, became a pretty successful businessman.
Not a million – not a kajillionaire, but quite comfortable.
My father wanted, I think, nothing to do with the life that his father would have liked
for him.
He served in the Army.
He graduated from the University of Vermont.
And I've interviewed him.
He came to the village in the mid-50s and wanted – I think part of it was he really
wanted none of the stuff that my grandfather had fought so hard for.
He didn't want the country club.
He didn't want the synagogue.
He didn't want the first-class cruises to Europe.
He wanted a more, I don't know, iconoclastic life.
My mother came from a completely different background.
She is Italian.
Her family was a noble family, a family of count and countess.
Her father – her mother was a countess and married her father, who was a military marine
engineer and whose grandfather had been the mayor of Milan at one point.
Anyway, they were a very well-to-do family, not hugely wealthy.
They were, unfortunately, on the wrong side of history.
They were supporters of the fascists.
They lost all of their estate and money in the war.
My mother married an American captain and came to this country when she was 18 and immediately
renounced her Italian citizenship.
She was so excited to come to New York.
Got annulled, went back to Europe, came back and forth.
But the short and the long of it is she met my father when she was in her late 20s.
I think she met him in the village.
I think she met him through his roommate at the time, a man named Alan Polikoff.
She met him at a party.
They fell in love.
They got married.
They shared, I think, a common value in just wanting to forge their own direction.
She didn't want anything to do with the Catholic Church or the old-fashioned Italian
life, northern Italian life.
They both loved being in the village.
They had very little money to speak of that I know of.
We had a very good life because my grandfather supported my education and that of my brother.
I have a brother born in 1962.
Around the time that he was born, first of all, just before he was born, we had an accident
in our house where I lit a match early in the morning when my mother was asleep.
The result was that I was burned, third-degree burns.
My mother heard me crying and rushed me to St. Vincent's Hospital where I was taken
care of.
But in those days, the parents weren't allowed to spend the night in the hospital.
You can imagine having a two-year-old child and essentially only being able to visit her
during visiting hours.
After two weeks of that, which I think is such a cruel practice, it's unbelievable
that that might have been standard practice.
After two weeks of that, my mom says I was so despondent and so distant from her that
she felt that it was an untenable situation and she worked very hard to be given permission
to continue caring for me at home.
She had to prove to the doctors that she could be an able nurse.
But that was our earliest experience with St. Vincent's Hospital.
Sometime in 1962 or 1963, shortly after my brother was born, we moved to 390 Bleeker
Street.
That is where I lived for the rest of my childhood and where my father still resides today.
We attended PS41.
My first grade teacher was Ms. Lori.
My second grade teacher was Mrs. Dwarren.
I think my third grade teacher was named Mrs. Klein or Mrs. Kleinman or something like
that.
But after that, when my brother started school, they didn't think that the public school was
right for him.
He ended up enrolling in Bank Street School.
Since they switched him, they switched me too.
Bank Street School, which still exists, was actually at the time on Bank Street, at 69
Bank Street.
In fourth grade, I started at Bank Street and I was able to walk to school, which was
hugely liberating at the time.
The village was always a safe neighborhood in my experience of it, but it was hardly
a tony neighborhood.
My mother loved it because there were a lot of Italian Americans there, so she was able
to find espresso before anyone used to really use that.
She used to be able to talk with certain shopkeepers in Italian.
I think there were probably also a lot of Irish people in the neighborhood.
We didn't have any neighborhood friends.
We had friends who lived in the village, and of course I had friends from school, all of
whom lived in the village.
But we didn't have friends from the street.
We had friends from our institutions.
We had friends from school.
What was on my street?
There was a man named Joe.
He was such a nice man.
He was an old Italian man.
I think he lived with a granddaughter or a daughter maybe named Cynthia.
I think we played with her at some point, but I don't think I really knew her.
I think she was at 388 Bleaker Street.
But anyway, Joe had a chair.
He used to sit on the sidewalk and he would say hello to everybody and he was a fixture
on the street.
Everybody knew Joe.
I didn't know anything about him.
I didn't know what his work had been.
I didn't know what his last name was.
I'd never entered his house, but there was never a day I remember that you would come
home that you didn't say hello to Joe.
On the corner of 11th and Bleaker, where the Marc Jacobs bookstore is now, was the candy
store which was run by Andy.
I think his son at some point, his name I can't remember.
We knew it as a candy store.
It was like, you know, cigarettes and newspapers.
I remember it being sort of dark and kind of smelly, but it had everything.
And Andy was a very nice man.
Heavy, big sort of lumbering body, a big flat face, gray hair.
I think he always had a cigar stub in his mouth, but I could be adding that to the history.
We used to go to Europe in the summer every other year to visit my mother's family.
And when we came back, I remember he would often give us a treat, a piece of gum or a
pretzel stick, and we always thought that that was incredibly kind of him.
He was also a fixture on the street.
In my memory, we had a commercial space on the ground floor of our house.
When I became conscious of it, it was always an antique store of some form or another.
There were a few antique stores on the street when I was a kid.
There was also a leather shop.
And I remember the woman who, there was a couple who ran it.
His name I think was Walter, and I think her name might have been Selina or something.
But she was very clearly Jewish, and he was black.
And they had a leather making shop, very sort of hippie style.
And he smoked a pipe.
And I just remember finding it interesting.
It was an interracial couple that was the first that I guess I had seen.
And they were there for a very, very long time.
I remember that there was a hardware store on Perry and Hudson.
And I think that there was a deli where the Ralph Lauren store is now on Bleeker and Perry.
And the street was really for people who used it, for people who lived there.
It was, I mean I guess actually eventually became more known for its antique stores.
In high school I remember there was a cute little store called Johnny Jupiter at 392
Perry Street.
They ultimately moved uptown.
There was a plant store where one of the Marc Jacobs stores is now on Perry and Bleeker.
There was a bird store where the Bond store is now on Bleeker between Perry and 11th.
So I guess the tone of the stores became a little bit more hippie-ish as we moved into
the later 60s.
Let's see, after Bank Street, Bank Street at one point moved uptown to where it resides
today on 114th Street.
And there were some families that didn't want to go uptown with it.
So they began, they founded a school with one of the administrators of the school.
They founded Village Community School.
And I entered that school in sixth grade in the fall of 1970.
And we were the first class of the school to graduate in 1973.
And because my last name is double A, I can say that I was the first person to ever graduate
from that school.
In my memory, all these elegant brownstones on Perry Street and Charles Street and 11th
Street were not single-family homes.
They were all broken up into apartments.
And I'm sure that there were some that were single-family homes, but in my memory, most
of them were broken up into apartments.
And we didn't know anyone that was wealthy.
I mean, maybe there were wealthy people.
There was one person I knew, Annie Esty.
I think her family had come from some advertising money.
And in fact, her father and mother or her mother and stepfather or something were the
only people who had a naming opportunity at Village Community School.
There's a library named after the Esty family.
There's nothing else in that school named after anyone.
But I remember she lived on East 11th Street, and she had a townhouse, and she had, like,
I remember, a big romper room.
And I remember realizing that she was wealthy.
But other friends of mine, Allison Kalfus and her sister Lisa lived on Perry Street,
and their mom was a single mom.
My friend Esme and her sister Phoebe lived on Perry Street, and their mom was a single
mom.
My best friend in school was Andri Reisdorf.
I met her the first day of first grade at PS 41, and she lived at 188 Spring Street,
which at the time was like saying she lived in Siberia.
The story about her that I knew was that her father, who was an expert cabinetmaker, had
been offered a home at 188 Spring Street if he agreed to renovate 188 and I guess 190
Spring Street.
And so Andri, who lived in this no man's land of Spring Street between Thompson and Sullivan,
she lived in a four-story townhouse that had a pool in the backyard and was filled with
antiques and was very beautiful.
But I always thought that they were sort of well off, but I don't even, her mother was
an advertising rep, and they eventually, Ken Reisdorf started Ken's Broom Street Bar.
It was originally Ken and John's Broom Street Bar, and then it became Ken and Bob's Broom
Street Bar.
Ken went into partnership with his brother, and I think maybe now it's just called Ken's
Broom Street Bar.
But they were really there in Soho from long before it was ever called Soho.
It was an Italian neighborhood.
I know I'm digressing a little bit because that's really Soho and not the village, but
it was related.
Andri went to village schools all the way through.
